title: For Sale/Trade:  Stevens 23 Little Sure Shot
postcontent: I have a Very, Very Rare J. Stevens #23 Little Sure Shot 22LR.Very Good Condition! Mechanically sound and does fire 22LR very accurately. Lock up is tight. Duck tape wrapped around stock to keep it from being loose. No observable cracks near the taping.This is the rarest STEVENS boy's rifle to find in any condition and a prize for any Boy's Rifle Collector. Sitting Bull named this gun for Annie Oakley. He called her, "Little Sure Shot." Arm & Tool on the barrel. Most Stevens Collectors have never seen a Stevens Sure Shot. This is likely the only one you will ever see. Gun shoots and functions with all original parts. Gun manufactured between 1884 and 1887; no C&R or FFL needed. The No. 23 Sure Shot Rifle made in the period circa 1894-circa 1896. This rifle is, perhaps, the rarest Stevens production single shot rifle made.James J. Grant, single shot rifle authority and author of the 1991 copyright work,"Boys Single Shot Rifles", states that he has seen only seven Sure Shot rifles in a life time of studying single shot firearms. Mr. Grant and others speculate that an unidentified period picture of a woman in frontier clothing holding a "Sure Shot" rifle is a Young Annie Oakley (called Little Miss Sure Shot by Sitting Bull)Check 5H-069 Flayderman "Very Scarce"!
